            <!-- 13. LOGICAL SHIFTS -->
            <section>
                <h3>What Are Logical Shifts?</h3>
                <div class="key-term fragment">
                    <h3>Logical Shift</h3>
                    <p>Moving all bits left or right, filling with zeros; bits shifted out are lost.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="cols">
                    <div class="box fragment">
                        <strong>Why It Exists</strong>
                        <ul class="small-text">
                            <li>Fast multiply/divide by 2 for unsigned values</li>
                            <li>Bit-manipulation in low-level code</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="box-blue fragment">
                        <strong>Clarify</strong>
                        <p class="small-text">Left shift multiplies by 2; right shift divides by 2 (truncates).</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <section>
                <section data-background="#e6f0fa">
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>How do logical shifts change a number?</strong></p>
                        <p class="small-text">Press Down to see examples.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>Left Shift by 1:</strong> 00110101 → 01101010 (×2)</p>
                        <p class="small-text">53 → 106</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>Right Shift by 2:</strong> 10110000 → 00101100 (÷4)</p>
                        <p class="small-text">176 → 44</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="box-blue">
                        <p><strong>Check:</strong> What happens to bits that fall off the edge?</p>
                        <p class="small-text">They are lost forever; zeros fill the gaps.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
            </section>

            <!-- 14. TWO'S COMPLEMENT INTRO -->
            <section>
                <h3>What Is Two's Complement?</h3>
                <div class="key-term fragment">
                    <h3>Two's Complement</h3>
                    <p>Binary system to represent negative integers using the MSB as a sign and inversion+1 to form negatives.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="cols">
                    <div class="box fragment">
                        <strong>Why It Exists</strong>
                        <ul class="small-text">
                            <li>Enables addition/subtraction with the same adder hardware</li>
                            <li>Only one representation of zero</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                    <div class="box-blue fragment">
                        <strong>Range</strong>
                        <p class="small-text">8-bit: -128 to +127 (MSB = 1 means negative)</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- 15. TWO'S COMPLEMENT: HOW (VERTICAL STEPS) -->
            <section>
                <section data-background="#e6f0fa">
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>How do we represent -25 in two's complement (8-bit)?</strong></p>
                        <p class="small-text">Press Down to see each step.</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>Step 1:</strong> Write +25 in 8 bits → 00011001</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>Step 2:</strong> Invert bits → 11100110</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="question-box">
                        <p style="font-size:1.2em; margin:0;"><strong>Step 3:</strong> Add 1 → <strong>11100111</strong></p>
                    </div>
                </section>
                <section>
                    <div class="box-blue">
                        <p><strong>Check:</strong> Convert back: invert (00011000) +1 → 00011001 = 25 → sign bit 1 → -25</p>
                    </div>
                </section>
            </section>

            <!-- 16. TWO'S COMPLEMENT Clarification -->
            <section>
                <h3>Clarify: Two's Complement</h3>
                <div class="question-box">Why is there only one zero in two's complement?</div>
                <div class="fragment box-blue">
                    <p><strong>Because</strong> the inversion+1 method makes the all-zeros pattern unique; no negative zero.</p>
                </div>
            </section>

